This paper focuses on the process of peer review meetings, which is a common practice in software engineering (cs.SE) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC) research. The paper also uses protocol analysis, which is a method commonly used in the field of computer-supported cooperative work (cs.CY). Additionally, the paper discusses the roles of participants in the review process, which could be relevant to the fields of computer engineering (cs.CE) and computational linguistics (cs.CL) as well.
